<TITLE> Rahul Gandhi courts allies </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, May 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The following is a snapshot of recent developments in India's general election campaign. (The sources are mentioned in brackets). Rahul Gandhi said he was confident of the leftist parties' support and praised other leading politicians outside the ruling coalition, in what was seen as trying to court potential allies in the scramble to build a coalition after the polls. Gandhi, one of Congress' star campaigners, said at a press conference in New Delhi: "I am confident that left will support a Congress prime minister." The communist parties quit the Congress-led coalition last year in protest against a civilian nuclear deal with the United States and so far ruled out rejoining Congress. Gandhi praised Nitish Kumar, the chief minister of Bihar, a potential swing state in which Kumar may rob Congress' current allies of crucial seats. There has been speculation Kumar could tie-up Congress, which he has denied. (The Asian Age, The Times of India
